52: /**
53:  * A client that consumes records from a Kafka cluster.
54:  * <p>
55:  * This client transparently handles the failure of Kafka brokers, and transparently adapts as topic partitions
56:  * it fetches migrate within the cluster. This client also interacts with the broker to allow groups of
57:  * consumers to load balance consumption using <a href="#consumergroups">consumer groups</a>.
58:  * <p>
59:  * The consumer maintains TCP connections to the necessary brokers to fetch data.
60:  * Failure to close the consumer after use will leak these connections.
61:  * The consumer is not thread-safe. See <a href="#multithreaded">Multi-threaded Processing</a> for more details.
62:  *
63:  * <h3>Cross-Version Compatibility</h3>
64:  * This client can communicate with brokers that are version 0.10.0 or newer. Older or newer brokers may not support
65:  * certain features. For example, 0.10.0 brokers do not support offsetsForTimes, because this feature was added
66:  * in version 0.10.1. You will receive an {@link org.apache.kafka.common.errors.UnsupportedVersionException}
67:  * when invoking an API that is not available on the running broker version.
68:  * <p>
69:  *
70:  * <h3>Offsets and Consumer Position</h3>
71:  * Kafka maintains a numerical offset for each record in a partition. This offset acts as a unique identifier of
72:  * a record within that partition, and also denotes the position of the consumer in the partition. For example, a consumer
73:  * which is at position 5 has consumed records with offsets 0 through 4 and will next receive the record with offset 5.
74:  * Note that offsets are not guaranteed to be consecutive (such as compacted topic or when records have been produced
75:  * using transactions). For example, if the consumer did read a record with offset 4, but 5 is not an offset
76:  * with a record, its position might advance to 6 (or higher) directly. Similarly, if the consumer's position is 5,
77:  * but there is no record with offset 5, the consumer will return the record with the next higher offset.
78:  * There are actually two notions of position relevant to the user of the consumer:
79:  * <p>
80:  * The {@link #position(TopicPartition) position} of the consumer gives the offset of the next record that will be given
81:  * out. It will be one larger than the highest offset the consumer has seen in that partition. It automatically advances
82:  * every time the consumer receives messages in a call to {@link #poll(Duration)}.
83:  * <p>
84:  * The {@link #commitSync() committed position} is the last offset that has been stored securely. Should the
85:  * process fail and restart, this is the offset that the consumer will recover to. The consumer can either automatically commit
86:  * offsets periodically; or it can choose to control this committed position manually by calling one of the commit APIs
87:  * (e.g. {@link #commitSync() commitSync} and {@link #commitAsync(OffsetCommitCallback) commitAsync}).
88:  * <p>
89:  * This distinction gives the consumer control over when a record is considered consumed. It is discussed in further
90:  * detail below.
91:  *
92:  * <h3><a name="consumergroups">Consumer Groups and Topic Subscriptions</a></h3>
93:  *
94:  * Kafka uses the concept of <i>consumer groups</i> to allow a pool of processes to divide the work of consuming and
95:  * processing records. These processes can either be running on the same machine or they can be
96:  * distributed over many machines to provide scalability and fault tolerance for processing. All consumer instances
97:  * sharing the same {@code group.id} will be part of the same consumer group.
98:  * <p>
99:  * Each consumer in a group can dynamically set the list of topics it wants to subscribe to through one of the
100:  * {@link #subscribe(Collection, ConsumerRebalanceListener) subscribe} APIs. Kafka will deliver each message in the
101: ","url":"https://sourcegraph.sourcegraph.com/github.com/sg-evals/kafka--0753c489@31d9200189f81283bf60e929ddc38fd68ac034e2/-/blob/clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/KafkaConsumer.java%3FL1-100"}

